  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions to combat money laundering:\n\n1. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n2. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n- Issues recommendations for international financial regulations\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank\n- Provide guidelines and support for anti-money laundering efforts\n\n5. Regional Regulations\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Similar regulations in North America, Asia, and other regions\n\nThese laws typically require:\n- Financial institutions to verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Cooperate with international investigations\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, making money laundering a criminal offense with potential significant penalties.",
